column168: Delivery Driver was going to make a delivery, he thought he was at the customer location, stopped on the road, noticed the address and found he was at the wrong house number, Driver started to drive on, the wheels started spinning on the ice, the back end of the truck started to slide to the right side of the road, the back tire caught the edge of the road and started to slide in the ditch, the whole truck followed, the truck went into a deep ditch, and was leaning, still on two tires.  Fire department hazmat and State Police responded, sand had to be put down before the wrecker could come out to pull the truck out, there was a wrecker service that did responded to pull the truck out of the ditch, the homes were evacuated and this section of road closed off due to the possible damager of the propane. column169: Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers.  Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.  The Company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions ore appropriate.

column168: During unloading at the consignee, they observed a small quantity of liquid on the trailer floor under one pallet of H/M.  They broke down the pallet and found one pail leaking at the point where its bail attaches to the pail’s shell.  The consignee refused the pail but accepted the balance of the shipment.  The driver acquired a containment for the pail and transported it back to the carrier's facility.
column169: This incident appears to be the result of the bail (lifting handle) of one pail being forced tightly against the pail's shell.  When the shipper stacked the pallet, at least one pail's bail was tightly against an adjacent pail.  The pallet was tightly shrink wrapped.  Shippers need to pay closer attention to ensuring that bails are turned so that there is no force against them.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN PASCAGOULA, MS, REPORTED THAT TANK CAR, GATX 70959, LOAD NITRIC ACID, HAD PRODUCT SLOSH FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER, MISSISSIPPI CHEMICAL WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT LIQUID PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE WHICH WAS CLOSED.  THE GASKET ON THE LIQUID LINE VALVE CAP WAS DEFECTIVE AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT.  THE CONTRACTOR FIRST RELIEVED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  HE THEN CONSTRUCTED A TEFLON ROPE TEMPORARY GASKET AND INSTALLED IT IN THE CAP.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF DEFECT DISCOVERED ON THE CAR AND THEY WILL REPLACE THE GASKET WHEN THE CAR RETURNS.
column169: RECOMMENDED TO SHIPPER THAT THEY SHOULD INSPECT AND POSSIBLY REPLACE THE LIQUID BALL VALVE WHEN THE CAR RETURNS.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S BOYLES YARD IN BIRMINGHAM, AL, CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER DISCOVERED TANK CAR, GATX 55482, LOAD HOT SIUM ALUMINATE, TO SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE SHIPPER, SOUTHERN IONICS, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  INSPECTION OF TOP FITTINGS ON CAR REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS PROTRUDING OUT FROM UNDER THE MANWAY COVER.  THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE NOZZLE TYPE GASKET WHICH HAD DEFORMED APPARENTLY DUE TO THE HEAT OF THE PRODUCT AND WHEN THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURED A PORTION OF THE GASKET PROTRUDED OUT FROM UNDER THE MANWAY COVER PREVENTING THE COVER FROM BEING SECURED LIQUID TIGHT.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER REPLACED THE DEFORMED AND DAMAGED GASKET WITH A NEW NITRILE NOZZLE TYPE GASKET.  HE SECURED THE MANWAY COVER WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  THE DEFECT DISCOVERED ON THIS CAR WAS DISCUSSED WITH SOUTHERN IONICS.

UTLX 900270 WAS INVOLVED IN A MULTI-CAR DERAILMENT WHICH RESULTED IN A BREACH IN THE TANK SHELL RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 60 TONS OF LIQUEFIED CHLORINE.  NINE FATALITIES INCLUDING ONE EMPLOYEE RESULTED FROM THE CHLORINE RELEASE.  COST FIGURES ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT ARE ESTIMATES AND WILL CHANGE OVER TIME.  A TOTAL OF FIVE RAILCARS (FOUR TANK CARS AND ONE FLATCAR) HAVE BEEN DESIGNATED BY THE NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY BOARD FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND TESTING AT CERTIFIED TANK CAR SHOPS.  THIS INCIDENT REMAINS UNDER ACTIVE INVESTIGATION.  NOTE PART III, LINE ITEM 25, CODE 309 (PUNCTURED) WAS SELECTED FROM THE LIST OF OPTIONS AVAILABLE TO DESIGNATE HOW THE PACKAGE FAILED.  EXACTLY HOW THE PACKAGE FAILED AND THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF THE PACKAGE FAILURE REMAIN UNDER INVESTIGATION BY THE NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY BOARD.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS ARE PENDING INVESTIGATION BY NATIONAL TRANSPROTATION SAFETY BOARD.

column168: THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (LDEQ) NOW HAS AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE DIVISION AND IS CURRENTLY INSPECTING RAILCARS FOR FUGITIVE EMISSIONS, AS THE EMISSIONS MAY POSSIBLY IMPACT THE AIR QUALITY OF NON-ATTAINMENT AREAS.  THE LDEQ IS FOCUSING ON A CERTAIN COMMODITY GROUP AND ARE NOT INSPECTING FOR LEAKS WITH CONVENTIONAL MEANS.  THEY ARE USING PID (PHOTO IONIZATION DETECTION) AND FID (FLAME IONIZING DETECTION).  ON JANUARY 5, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 11:25 HOURS, RAILWAY CAR GLNX 34155, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINING ISOBUTYLENE, FLAMMABLE GAS, UN1055, WAS REPORTED LEAKING DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND THE LDEQ AT THE MARYLAND, LOUISIANA, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) RAIL YARD.  THE LDEQ DETECTED A LEAK USING A FIELD INSTRUMENT (IN A VERY LOW PARTS PER MILLION (PPM)).  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WHO DISCOVERED TWO LOOSE LIQUID LINE PLUGS AND A LOOSE VAPOR LINE PLUG (HAND TIGHT).  THE TEAM TIGHTENED THE PLUGS, THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.  NOTE PART III, QUESTION 32, RESPONSE COST, INCLUDES CARRIER AND SHIPPER COSTS ONLY.  PART III, QUESTION 25 (CAUSE CODES).  THERE WERE NO DEFECTIVE VALVES OR DEVICE FAILURES, ONLY LOOSE CLOSURES, WHICH WERE SECURED SIMPLY BY TIGHTENING THE CLOSE.  QUESTION 28 (IF VALVE OR DEVICE FAILED) NO TYPE, MANUFACTURER OR MODEL NUMBER IS MARKED, SINCE THERE WERE ONLY LOOSE CLOSURES.
column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH RELEASE INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

Eagle Global has been notified of this requirement and the importance of doing this in the future.

During preparation for transprotation, the pails were loaded onto a trailer however they were not secured to a pallet. During transportation they were damaged by other freight on the truck due to them not being secured. Holes in the pails were located on the body. The spill was cleaned up back at the Jevic terminal and the duration of the spill was less then one hour. Loader personnel will be additionally trained in the safe securing of smaller containers in a trailer with other large pieces freight.

column168: Accident:  At O5lO on 1/1/2005, the pharmacist on-duty, Michael Badrian and the RSO, Matt Komornik received a call from our driver, Ebot Obeti stating that he was in an accident. He stated that cans were in the middle of the road. Oben stated that a drunk driver ran him off the road and fled the scene. Once the authorities arrived, our driver was talcen by ambulance to North Arundel Hospital. The RSO was dispatched to the scene and our driver from the Delaware pharmacy was sent across the bridge to the scene of the accident.  The accident happened on Eastbound Route 50, just prior to the Cape St. Claire Exit. This location is in Annapolis, Maryland, Anne Arundel County.  Scene:  Our RSO arrived on the scene at 0600. He assessed the damage to the truck and to the ammo cans. He was told that a vial had come out of the lead viai shield. After about 15 minutes, he discovered what was left of the vial in the middie of the road. He began to survey the area and measured the surface at 40 mR/hr. The size of the contaminated area was approximately 100 ft. Matt began to follow the trail of contamination, which lead to our Seaford vehicle that had come across the Bay Bridge to the scene of the accident. The passenger side tires were reading about 50 mRJhr on the surface. (We assume the drIver ran over the vial in the road.) The trail of contamination ended at this vehicle. The vial that was crushed was an 8 mCi multidose vial of MA.A calibrated at 1400 on 1/1/05.  Matt began to match up cans to the shipping certificates. After doing so, he found that a can was missing. After Matt and James Parker, the Seaford driver continued to search the area, they found the magnet and the 2 placards that matched this can. No can was ever found. The vehicle involved in the accident was surveyed and no contamination was present. The State Police had the vehicle towed prior to 0720.  Sherry Miller, the pharmacy manager arrived on the scene around 0720 andshortly after this, Robert Nelson from MDE also arrived on the scene. Mr. Nelson had H.AZMAT decontaminate the surface of the road and the wheels of the Seaford vehicle. This was done with high-powered water sprayed on the surface, which washed the contamination into a designated area along Route 50’s median. The highway was shutdown during this process — which may have lasted 20 minutes. After this procedure, the Seaford vehicle was not reading at the surface and the roadway was reading approximately 2 m.Rtbr. We released the Seaford driver and the roadway was re-opened.  The remaining cans and the spill kit and contents, along with a brush from the HAZMAT team were removed from the scene by Sherry Miller and James Parker. James Parker removed cans that were intact and no contamination.. Sherry Miller took cans that were intact and the clean-up material.

column168: DURING UNLOADING OF A TANL TRUCK OF FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS AT RESILITE, THE CUSTOMER'S TANK OVERFLOWED RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 25-30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WHICH THE CUSTOMER CLEANED UP AND ASSUMED RESPONSIBILITY. THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS A FROZEN STORAGE TANK GAUGE WHICH INDICATED AVAILABLE SPACE TO UNLOAD FULL CONTENTS OF TANK TRUCK PRIOR TO HOOKUPS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1400HRS ON 1-12-2005, A TRUCK DRIVER WAS UNLOADING SODIUM BISULFITE SOLUTION FROM THE CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE (CTMV) TO THE PLANT STORAGE TANK USING PLANT AIR PRESSURE.  THE CTMV WAS SPOTTED ON THE LINED CONCRETE CONTAINMENT PAD ADJACENT TO THE STORAGE TANK.  AT THE END OF THE UNLOADING PROCESS (APPROXIMATELY 1425 HRS) THE AIR WAS BLOWN THROUGH THE UNLOADING HOSE, AND INTO THE STORAGE TANK.  THE AIR EXITED THE STORAGE TANK THROUGH THE TANK'S 2-INCH VENT.  THE STORAGE TANK HAD BEEN FILLED ABOVE ITS INTENDED "FULL" VOLUME.  THE AIR ESCAPING THROUGH THE VENT ENTRAINED SOME OF THE SOLUTION, RESULTING IN A SMALL AMOUNT OF SODIUM BISULFITE SOLUTION MIST.  WE ESTIMATE THE AMOUNT OF SOLUTION ESCAPING AS A MIST TO BE LESS THAN 1 GALLON.  THE RELEASE LASTED FOR LESS THAN 1 MINUTE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR PERSONNEL EXPOSURES.  THE TANK CAR DID NOT FAIL.  NO MATERIAL WAS OBSERVED ON THE GROUND, OR IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE OPERATOR WHO HAD BEEN OBSERVING THE UNLOADING REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE TEAM LEADER WHO INVESTIGATED THE AREA AND SUBSEQUENTLY REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO MANAGEMENT.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS A HIGHER THAN EXPECTED LEVEL IN THE STORAGE TANK.  THE ORDER WAS PLACED IN 22,300LBS (2,000GAL), HOWEVER 28,460LBS (2,550GAL) WERE UNLOADED INTO THE TANK.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDED 1) COMMUNICATIONS WITH THE SUPPLIER REGARDING THE AMOUNT SHIPPED; AND 2) COMMUNICATIONS WITH PLANT OPERATORS TO CHECK THE AMOUNT OF THE ACTUAL SHIPMENT VS. THE AMOUNT ORDERED.

column168: FUEL DELIVERY DRIVER WAS MAKING A GASOLINE DELIVERY TO WAWA STORE #926 LOCATED AT 2615 E. CHESTNUT AVENUE, VINELAND, NJ.  DRIVER CONNECTED VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE TO GROUND CONNECTION AND TRAILER.  HE NEXT CONNECTED HIS DELIVERY HOSES TO THE GROUND CONNECTION AND TO THE TRAILER.  WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE DELIVERY VALVE ON #4 COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER, THE GASKET BLEW OUT FROM THE AREA BEHIND THE SITE GLASS ON THE DELIVERY TUBE.  PRODUCT WAS SPRAYING OUT FROM UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CONCRETE UNLOADING PAD.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE #4 COMPARTMENT DELIVERY VALVE AND THE TRAILER INTERNAL SAFETY VALVES FOR ALL COMPARTMENTS.  BECUASE THE DELIVERY TUBE STILL HAD PRODUCT IN IT, IT CONTINUES TO LEAK UNDER THE TRAILER, BUT DUE TO THE HEAVY RAIN, SOME PRODUCT ENTERED THE DRAIN.  THE VINELAND, NJ FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND SHORTLY AFTER, THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED.  THE HAZMAT TEAM PUT BOOMS DOWN AROUND THE STORM DRAIN OUTLET WHICH EMPTIES INTO A BASIN AREA LOCATED BEHIND THE STORE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD WAWA CLOSE THE STORE FOR APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES TO MINIMIZE TRAFFIC IN THE STORE PARKING LOT.  HAZMAT PERSONNEL ALLOWED THE DRIVER TO DRAIN THE COMPARTMENT TUBE INTO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  THE DRIVER STUCK NUMBER FOUR COMPARTMENT AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 39 GALLONS HAD BEEN LOST.  THE DEFECTIVE GASKET WAS REPLACED ON SITE AND THE ENTIRE GASOLINE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  WAWA CORPORATION HAD LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS DISPATCHED TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL AND THEY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE SHORTLY AFTER THE DRIVER COMPLETED HIS GASOLINE DELIVERY.  LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANED THE CONCRETE PAD AND SURROUNDING AREA AND TOOK ADDITIONAL CLEANUP MEASURES IN THE DRAIN BASIN AREA BEHIND THE STORE.  THREE DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED SPILL PADS, ABSORBENT PADS AND OIL DRY MATERIAL WAS REMOVED BY THE CLEANUP CREW.  AS OF THE DATE OF THIS REPORT, LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS WAITING FOR THE FROZEN GROUND TO THAW TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP IN THE DRAIN BASIN AREA.  A FOLLOW-UP REPORT WILL BE SUBMITTED AT A LATER DATE.

column168: 1.) THE DRIVER STARTED LOADING HIS TRUCK AT 6:05 PM IN DES PLAINES, ILLINOIS AND FINISHED LOADING THE TRUCK AT 6:50 PM.  THE TRUCK WAS LOADED IN THIS MANNER BY COMPARTMENT #1.) 2,700 GALLONS #2 FUEL OIL  #2.)1,500 GALLONS REGULAR UNLEADED #3.) 1,300 GALLONS REGULAR UNLEADED  #4.) 2,800 GALLONS REGULAR UNLEADED  2.) THE DRIVER THEN LEFT DES PLAINES, ILLINOIS AND DROVE TO THE BP AMOCO STATION LOCATED AT 5 W IRVING PARK ROAD ROSELLE, ILLINOIS 60172 AND ARRIVED THERE AT 7:38 PM.  3.)  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD THE 1,500 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED IN COMPARTMENT #2 WITHOUT ANY PROBLEMS.  4.) THE DRIVER THEN SWITCHED TO COMPARTMENT #3 WHICH CONTAINED 1,300 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED.  WHEN THE DRIVER SWITCHED THE HOSE BETWEEN COMPARTMENTS THE DRIVER HAD TO PUSH ON THE HOSE A LITTLE BIT TO MOVE IT OVER TO COMPARTMENT #3 UNLOADING VALVE.  5.) THE DRIVER THEN SLOWLY STARTED OPENING THE UNLOADING VALVE AND SAW PRODUCT COMING UP FROM THE OVERFILL PROTECTION WELL WHERE THE UNLOADING CONNECTION IS LOCATED.  WHEN THE DRIVER PUSHED ON THE HOSE TO MOVE IT FROM COMPARTMENT #2 TO COMPARTMENT #3 IT INADVERTENTLY AND UNINTENTIONALLY UNLOCKED THE UNLOADING FITTING FROM THE FILL PIPE CONNECTOR.  6.) ESTIMATED TIME OF THE RELEASE IS 2-3 SECONDS.  7.) THE DRIVER ESTIMATED THAT THE TOTAL RELEASE WAS NO MORE THAN 3 GALLONS.  ACTIONS TAKEN AT TIME DISCOVERED.  1.) THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE UNLOADING VALVE TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  2.) THE STATION MANAGER WAS THERE WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED.  THE DRIVER AND THE STORE MANAGER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND OIL DRY.  3.) THE SPILL OCCURRED ON CONCRETE AND ASPHALT AND DUE TO THE IMMEDIATE RESPONSE ACTIONS TAKEN BY THE DRIVER AND STORE MANAGER; THE SPILL DID NOT IMPACT ANY SOIL OR GROUND/SURFACE WATER.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: A shipment of Uranium ore concentrates (natural mine processed ore) was received at Honeywell Metropolis Works Facility (MTW) on O73O 1-25-05. A 55-gallon drum inside the sea land container was found to be damaged during transport releasing ore inside the sea-land container. The damage was to the bottom lip of the drum. It had been bent approximately 3 inches in length at the seam which allowed the seam to open up —1/4 inch allowing material to be released from the drum during transit. Follow up radiological surveys indicated contamination outside the sea- land container at levels below DOT 49cfr 173.443 limits for removable contamination. Based on the loose material found inside the sea-land and the indication of contamination found outside the sea-land container, MTW personnel determined this was a reportable event due to the potential loss of radioactive material from the sea land containers according to 49cfr171 b 2 ( . . .,or suspected radioactive contamination occurs involving a radioactive material.)   The shipment receiver (MTW) halted all shipments that were in transit from the shipper (refused receipt) until the apparent cause to the failure could be determined and assurances that similar conditions were not present in other shipments in route. The shipping company representatives flew in from South Africa to investigate the failure with the carrier company. The investigation was initiated to determine why the 55-gal drum’s integrity had been compromised. The shipper, to assess the potential loss of material during transit, initiated inspection and radiological surveys of the areas the sea-land had been during transit. The additional shipments (sea-land containers in route) that were currently halted were assessed to evaluate for similar failures. No radioactive material was identified to be loss/released based on these inspections.   The damaged drum was weighed at MTW to assess the potential loss of material. 12 pounds of material was identified to be the difference between the shipped weight and the final weight. The amount cf material on the floor inside the sea-land was estimated to be approximately 12 pounds, indicating little if any loss of material while in transit.   The shipper determined that the drum base seam was most likely damaged (bent) while or prior to loading. This damage was further degraded during transport allowing material to leak out the bottom of the drum to the interior of the sea-land container. This is supported by a reports provided by the shipper and professional engineering consultant (attached).
column169: Based on a clear understanding of the potential cause and reasonable assurances that   contamination was not present on the remaining shipments, the receiver allowed the remaining sea-lands in transit to procedure to MTW. There were no additional failures experienced in the remaining shipments. The shipper is committed to review its loading and inspection procedures to assure this type of failures will not be experienced in future shipments.

column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW REPORTED CRGX 30051 DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) IN THE RAILYARD & IT WAS ISOLATED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA WITH RECEPTACLE PLACED UNDER BOV TO CATCH DROPLETS.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDER REPORTED FINDING THE PRIME BOV CLOSED & THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) TOOL TIGHT, BUT THREADS AROUND BOC WERE PRODUCT WET.  SHIPPER CONTRACT MOBILE REPAIR UNIT RESPONDING DETERMINED THAT THE BOC COULD NOT BE REMOVED WITHOUT RISKING A LARGER VOLUME OF PRODUCT RELEASE.  SINCE THE PRODUCT DRIP COULD NOT BE STOPPED, CRGX 30051 BECAME A CANDIDATE FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER. PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED ON 1/27/05 BY 1115 HRS. CST BY SHIPPER CONTRACTORS INTO TILX 290452 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENTS. AFTERWARDS, THE BOC GASKET FROM CRGX 30051 WAS CHECKED & FOUND TO BE AGE DETERIORATED & GROOVED.  THE BOV (MIDLAND VALVE), ALTHOUGH IN A CLOSED POSITION, ALLOWED PRODUCT TO BYPASS THIS CLOSED VALVE.  SHIPPER DIRECTED CRGX 30051 TO THE NEAREST REPAIR FACILITY.  SPILLAGE IN RECEPTACLE EVAPORATED & GROUND IMPACT WAS MINIMAL.

BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZMAT RESPONDER TOOL TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) & DRIPPING EBBED TO ONE OR TWO DROPLETS EVERY 15 MINUTES.  RESPONDER THEN REMOVED BOC & THE BOC GASKET. AFTERWARDS, ACFX 76666 WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION. ON 1/19/05, A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR NOTICED UTLX 202752 OVER THE DRIP PIT & NOTIFIED THE BNSF LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, WHOM INITIATED THE BNSF NOTIFICATION PROTOCOL.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS REMOVED SEAL 441259 FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER & FOUND THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE OPEN ONE FULL TURN AND THE CLOSURE PLUG HANGING FROM ITS CHAIN, NOT APPLIED.  RESPONDERS CLOSED SAMPLE VALVE & APPLIED CLOSURE PLUG, ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE BY 1420 HRS. CST, 1/19/05.  THE KCFD ALSO RESPONDING, ARRIVED AFTER THE SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED & BEING SATISFIED THAT THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS SECURED, DEPARTED SITE SHORTLY AFTER ARRIVAL.  A REWEIGH OF UTLX 202752 INDICATED A 1400 POUND DIFFERENCE, EQUATING TO AN APPROXIMATE 212 GALLONS OF PRODUCT VARIANCE.  THE DRIP PIT CONTAINED MOST OF THIS PRODUCT LOSS ALONG WITH AN ACCUMULATION OF WATER AND ICE.  A BNSF CONTRACT RESPONSE TEAM VACUUMED OR PUMPED ALL LIQUID FROM THE PIT INTO A POLY STORAGE TANK FOR FUTURE APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL.

column168: BNSF MECHANICAL CARMAN REPORTED CELX 11217 IN RAILYARD DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE'S FLANGE AREA.  BNSF HAZ RESPONDER PLACED RECEPTACLE UNDER DRIP AREA AND TIGHTENED ALL FLANGE BOLTS; BUT 1 OF 10 COULD NOT BE FULLY TIGHTENED.  SHIPPER CONTRACT MOBILE REPAIR CREW CALLED TO ASSIST AND THIS ONE FLANGE BOLT STILL COULD NOT BE FULLY TIGHTENED.  DRIPPING CONTINUED AND CELX 11217 BECAME A CANDIDATE FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER  CELX 11217 WAS TO BE FURTHER ISOLATED IN RAILYARD.  WIND SHIFTED SENDING PRODUCT ODOR TOWARDS ADJACENT OFF-PROPERTY WAREHOUSE BUILDING.  ONE OF SEVERAL AIR EXCHANGERS FOR THIS BUILDING (ANDERSON MERCHANDISING, APPROX. 600 FEET AWAY) SUCKED IN PRODUCT ODOR.  LOCAL FD/EMS CALLED AFTER 12 ANDERSON EMPLOYEES COMPLAINED ABOUT A CHEMICAL ODOR AND ILLNESS.  TWO OF THESE IMPACTED ANDERSON EMPLOYEES WENT TO LOCAL HOSPITAL ER FOR DIAGNOSIS.  THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.  ALLEEDLY, 4 OTHER ANDERSON EMPLOYEES SOUGHT MEDICAL TREATMENT FROM THEIR PERSONAL PHYSICIANS.  ANDERSON'S WORKFORCE ON THEIR FIRST SHIFT WERE SENT HOME TWO HOURS BEFORE THE END OF THEIR SHIFT.  ANDERSON ALSO OPTED TO CANCEL THEIR SECOND SHIFT.  THESE SHIFT CLOSINGS IMPACTED 300 WORKERS (150 TOTAL PER SHIFT).  LOCAL FD CLEARED SITE BY 1610 HRS. CST, ON 1/12 AFTER CELX 11217 WAS MOVED TO THE ZITA RAIL SIDING OUTSIDE OF AMARILLO IN A NON-POPULATED AREA.  PRODUCT TRANSFER AT ZITA FROM CELX 11217 TO CELX 11287 WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT BY 0600 HRS.  CST ON 1/13.  AFTER PRODUCT TRANSFER, ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED INSIDE CELX 11217 TO ENSURE NO FURTHER PRODUCT DRIPPAGE FROM ANY PRODUCT HEEL REMAINING IN TANK ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED INSIDE CELX 11217 TO ENSURE NO FURTHER PRODUCT DRIPPAGE FROM ANY PRODUCT HEEL REMAINING IN TANK CAR. FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL FRA-05010014 RECEIVED TO RETURN CELX 11217 TO SHIPPER FOR DETAILED FAILURE ANALYSIS.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THIS WAS THE FIRST LOADED TRIP FOR CELX 11217 AFTER QUALIFICATION BY SAFETY RAIWAY SERVICE IN VICTORIA, TX.

THE ONE-HALF MILE EVACUATION WAS PRECAUTIONARY AND IN ACCORDANCE WITH EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDELINES.  THE DILUTED MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION AND FURTHER HANDLING, TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DERAILMENT REMAINS UNDER ACTIVE INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON JANUARY 19, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 20:45 HOURS A RAILWAY CAR, GATX15245 LOADED WITH HYDROCHLORIC ACID, CORROSIVE UN1789, PG II, WAS REPORTED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCH AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) WESTLAKE YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED, AND A CONTRACTED RESPONDER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE, REPORTING A DETERIORATED RUPTURE DISK.  THE CONTRACTED RESPONDER REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE DISK, THUS CORECTING THE RELEASE.  TWO RAILROAD EMPLOYEES WERE REPORTED EXPOSED TO THE LEAKING TANK CAR.  A DOCTOR EVALUATED THE TWO EMPLOYEES AND THEY WERE RELEASED BACK TO NROMAL DUTY.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO TRANSPORTATION.
column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH RELEASE INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: THIS LIQUID BULK CARGO TANK TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH PHTHALIC ANHYDRIDE MOLTEN AT APPROXIMATELY 320'F AT THE BASF PLANT IN PASADENA, TX.  AS A RESULT OF THE AGE AND THE HOT TEMPERATURE OF THE PRODUCTS CARRIED ON THIS BULK TANK TRAILER (REPEATED HEATING AND COOLING CAUSING EXPANSION AND CONTRACTION OF TANK SHELL MATERIAL) A CRACK HAD DEVELOPED IN THE TANK SHELL APPROXIMATELY HALF WAY BACK AND NEAR THE TOP OF THE TANK.  THE STAINLESS STEEL CARGO TANK SHELL IS WRAPPED WITH INSULATION AND AN OUTER ALUMINUM SKIN WHICH PREVENTED EXTERIER VISUAL DETECTION OF THE CRACK.  WHEN THE DRIVER OF THIS UNIT STOPPED TO TAKE A BREAK AT THE TRUCK STOP IN MINDEN, LA.  HE NOTICED PRODUCT SEEPING OUT BETWEEN A SEAM OF THE TANK'S EXTERIOR SKIN AT THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE TANK.  PHTHALIC ANHYDRIDE MOLTEN BEGINS TO SOLIDIFY AT 264'F.  AS THE SEEPING PRODUCT WAS INTRODUCED TO THE COOLER AIR OUTSIDE OF THE TANK BODY IT IMMEDIATELY HARDENED FORMING A STALACTITE FORMATION AT THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE TRAILER BODY AND ALSO ACTED TO SEAL THE CRACK IN THE TANK SHELL.  SUBSEQUENTLY, NO PRODUCT EVER ACTUALLY LEAKED TO THE GROUND.  THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WERE NOTIFIED AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE SERVICE WERE CONTRACTED TO STANDBY.  THE PRODUCT WAS ALLOWED TO REMAIN IN A PARKED STATUS ON THE TANK TRAILER AND COOL UNTIL IT SOLIDIFIED INSIDE OF THE TANK.  THE CARGO TANK TRAILER WAS THEN LOADED ONTO A DROP DECK TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED TO OUR BRANCH IN DEER PARK, TX. TO AWAIT UNLOADING BACK AT THE SHIPPER'S PLANT.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SPILL LOCATION, THE RESPONSE TEAM UTILIZED A SEALANT PUTTY ON THE TRAILER UNDERCARRIAGE. CCX DRIVER WAS BEING LOADED AT RFS CABLEWAVE IN WALLINGFORD.  RFS EMPLOYEE WAS LOADING A REEL OF WIRE ONTO A 48 FOOT TRAILER.  HE PROCEEDED TO LOAD REEL WITH NO VISIABILITY OF DRUMS IN FRONT OF HIM.  HE HIT A HAZARDOUS DRUM OF ACETONE (FLAMMABLE) LIQUID.  THE LIQUID POURED OUT INTO A 45 FOOT TRAILER FROM FRONT TO BACK.  BOTTOM OF DRUM ABOUT 6 INCHES LONG AND WIDE FORCED LIQUID TO RUN OUT.  CCX DSR CALLED ME TO LET ME KNOW WHAT HAD HAPPENED.  THE ACCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO A RFS SUPERVISOR WHO THEN WENT TO GET ABSORBENT TO STOP LEAK INTO TRAILER.  THE LEAK WENT THROUGH FLOOR ONTO RFS PROPERTY.  THEY TOOK THEIR ABSORBENT TO DAM OFF THE LIQUID FROM RUNNING ANYWHERE ELSE.  I THEN CALLED THE CT DEP AND A CLEAN UP CREW TO LET THEM KNOW WHAT WAS HAPPENING.  I THEN WENT TO THE SCENE WITH ANOTHER DRIVER WITH SOME SPEEDY DRY AND SALVAGE DRUM TO HELP WITH CLEANUP.

THE BAG WAS DAMAGED BY ABRASION AGAINST THE TRAILER WALL DURING TRANSIT CAUSING RELEASE OF PRODUCT.              ALL PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.
THE PACKAGES BECAME DAMAGED DURING THE SORT.  STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED.

DURING THE SORT APPROXIMATELY 12 EMPLOYEES EXPERIENCED A BITTER TASTE IN THEIR MOUTHS.  SOME EXPERIENCED NAUSEA AND THREW UP.  OTHERS HAD HEADACHES.  THE WAREHOUSE AREA WAS CLEARED OF EMPLOYEES DURING THE SORT.  STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED.  THE PACKAGE CAUSING THE PROBLEM AT FIRST COULD NOT BE DETERMINED.  ALL PACKAGES WERE CHECKED BY THE SPILL SPECIALIST WHILE IN APPROPRIATE PPE.  SOME LOOSE WHITE POWDER MATERIAL WAS FOUND IN A ULD AND THIS WAS CLEANUP UP AFTER WE TOOK A SAMPLE TO BE SENT FOR ANALYSES AT A LAB.  ALL KNOWN CHEMICAL PACKAGES WERE OPENED TO LOOK FOR THE LEAKING PACKAGE; NONE FOUND AT THAT TIME.  SORT BEGAN AGAIN APR. 2 HOURS LATER.  DRIVER ON ROAD HAD BITTER TASTE IN HIS MOUTH.  PROBLEM PACKAGE ON HIS VEHICLE.  STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES COMPLETED.  ONE INNER VIAL HAD LEAKED OF THE 36 INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  NO RESIDUE FOUND ON OUTSIDE OF PACKAGE.  MSDS OBTAINED - PROPER SHIPPING, UN # INDICATED.  LC 50 NUMBERS INDICATE PACKING GROUP I PER IATA STANDARDS.
column169: SHIPPER CLAIMS PER PARTICLE SIZE OF THE MATERIAL THAT IT'S NOT REGULATED AS A TOXIC.  I SUGGESTED THAT THEY CONTACT THE MANUFACTURER TO SEE IF THEY AGREE AND WILL PROVIDE A NEW MSDS FOR FUTURE SHIPMENTS.  OR, THAT THE SHIPPER CONTACT DOT TO REQUEST A WRITTEN INTERPRETATION ON THEIR MSDS TO SEE IF THEY AGREE IT'S NON-HAZ.  FEDEX EXPRESS CORPORATE SAFETY/DG ADMIN WOULD EXPECT THEM TO SHIP IT AS A DG (TOXIC) UNLESS THEY HAVE PROOF THAT IT'S NOT TOXIC.  ALSO, EVEN IF NEW INFORMATION WERE TO INDICATE THAT IT'S NOT TOXIC FROM DOT OR MANUFACTURER, WHY WAS THIS MATERIAL NOT SENT AS AVIATION REGULATED SOLID, N.O.S, HAZARD CLASS 9, UN 3335.  IF LEAKAGE OR SPILLAGE OCCURS IN FLIGHT, IT APPEARS THAT THIS MATERIAL WOULD CAUSE DISCOMFORT TO CREW AND INTERFERE WITH ASSIGNED DUTIES.  WE BELIEVE THIS TO BE UNDECLARED DG EITHER WAY.

INSIDE WAS A WRAPPED GIFT AND INSIDE THAT WAS PERFUME, 2 BOTTLES OF 15 ML.  THE SHIPPER WHEN CONTACTED DID NOT HAVE A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) TO SHOW WHETHER OR NOT IT IS FLAMAMBLE.  I CHECKED THE MANUFACTURER'S WEB SITE (MANUFACTURER IN FRANCE).  NO MSDS'S FOUND ON WEB SITE.  AS THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS NOT OFFERED WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, LABELS, NOR WITH A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION, I SUSPECT UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS AS PERFUMERY PRODUCTS, 3, UN1266 SINCE THEIR IS NO MSDS TO THE CONTRARY.  ALCOHOL WAS LISTED AS THE PRIMARY INGREDIENT ON THE MANUFACTURER'S PRODUCT LABEL.  FAA CONTACTED.  PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: LIGHT VAN TRAVELING SOUTH ON RT 202 IN HARD RAIN / HIGH WIND (NO STREET LIGHTING) LOW VISIBILITY SUDDENLY CAME UPON DOWNED TREE ACROSS ROAD WHICH HAD CARRIED POWER LINES DOWN WITH IT.  DRIVER DID NOT SEE TREE UNTIL IT WAS TOO LATE AND VEHICLE IMPACTED TREE/WIRES CAUSING IT TO ROLL ONTO ITS SIDE OFF OF THE ROAD.  THE DRIVER WAS UNHURT AND EXITED THE VEHICLE.  POLICE RESPONDED AND WHEN DRIVER NOTIFIED THE POLICE THAT NUCLEAR MEDICINE WAS BEING TRANSPORTED, POLICE NOTIFIED VOL. FIRE WHO RESPONDED AND THEN DETAILED HAZMAT TEAM.  DUE TO INVOLVED OF DOWNED POWER LINES JERSEY CENTRAL P & L RESPONDED.  ROAD CLOSED UNTIL POWER LINE ISSUES RESOLVED.  THEN HAZMAT TEAM ASSESSED CARGO STATUS.  NO APPARENT DAMAGE TO FREIGHT AND BLOCKING/BRACING AND CONTAINERS WERE OBSERVED INTACT WITHIN VEHICLE.  DEL-MED, INC RSO IN CONTACT WITH HAZMAT TEAM WHO OBSERVED NO ELEVATED RADIATION LEVELS.  DRIVER AND DEL-MED SUPERVISOR RECOVERED FREIGHT INTO SECOND VEHICLE AND RETURNED PACKAGES TO SHIPPER FOR EVALUATION.  SWIPE TESTS CONFIRMED NO EXTERNAL CONTAMINATION OF PACKAGES OR VEHICLE.  VEHICLE EFFECTIVELY TOTALLED (LOSS OF $5000 INSURED).  ROADWAY REOPENED GRADUALLY WITH ONE LANE OPENED AFTER POWER LINE RESTORATION.  DURATION ~ 5 HRS.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT WAS VIRTUALLY UNAVOIDABLE GIVEN LOW VISIBILITY (SAM) AND HARD WIND/RAIN.  THE DRIVER COULD NOT HAVE KNOWN OF THE CIRCUMSTANCE BEFORE ENCOUNTER.  RELATIVELY SLOW SPEED IMPACT AVERTED THE OCCASION OF INJURY TO DRIVER.  BLOCKING AND BRACING CONFIGURATION WAS VERY EFFECTIVE IN AVERTING DAMAGE TO FREIGHT AND PACKAGING WAS EFFECTIVE IN PREVENTION OF RELEASE OF HAZMAT AND KEEPING CONTENTS INTACT AND UNDAMAGED.  NOTE: THIS REPORT PREPARED AND SUBMITTED IN LIEU OF COMPLETION OF ONLINE INCIDENT REPORT "698" REPORT E-2005020102 COULD NOT BE COMPLETED AND SHOULD BE WITHDRAWN/DELETED IN ITS INCOMPLETE STATUS.  NEW ONLINE REPORTING SYSTEM HAS GREAT PROMISE BUT STILL HAS SOME ISSUES WHEN REPORTING AN INCIDENT INVOLVING RAM.

A BNSF SOUTHBOUND TRAIN INCURRED A TRAIN SESPARATION BETWEEN THE REAR LOCOMOTIVE ON CONSIST AND THE FIRST RAILCAR IN THE TRAIN WHILE OPERATING ON SINGLE MAIN TRACK.  DURING THIS SEPARATION, THE RAILCAR CONSIST IMPACTED THE LOCOMOTIVE CONSIST WITH CLOSED COUPLERS.  THE TRAIN CREW RECOUPLED THE TRAIN.  THE CONDUCTOR WAS IN PROCESS OF INSPECTING THE REMAINDER OF THE TRAIN WHEN HE ENCOUNTERED A CHEMICAL ODOR AT LINE 40 (GATX 75680).  THE CONDUCTOR IMMEDIATELY RETURNED TO THE LOCOMOTIVE CONSIST, SETTING 18 HANDBRAKES ENROUTE.  THE CREW UNCOUPLED THE LOCOMOTIVE CONSIST AND OPERATED ENGINE LIGHT TO WESTWOOD WHERE THEY WERE MET BY WESTWOOD FD/EMS.  BOTH CONDUCTOR & ENGINEER WERE TAKEN TO LOCAL HOSPITAL COMPLAINING OF BACK PAIN FROM THE TRAIN RUN-IN.  THE CONDUCTOR WAS ALSO GIVEN OXYGEN OF CHEMICAL INHALATION EXPOSURE.  BOTH WERE TREATED & RELEASED.  THE COUNTY SHERIFF BEING NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT, CLOSED TWO NEARBY HIGHWAYS (STATE ROUTE 44 & COUNTY ROAD A-21) IN CASE OF A POSSIBLE DERAILMENT WITH A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAK.  TWO BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS ARRIVED & INSPECTED THE STANDING TRAIN CONSIST FINDING NO DERAILMENT.  THEY DID FIND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE (VRV) ON GATX 75680, MOST LIKELY FROM A HYDRAULIC PRESSURE SURGE OF THE LIQUID COMMODITY DURING THE TRAIN RUN-IN IMPACT EVENT.  THE VRV WAS REMOVED & A PIPE PLUG WAS SECURED IN THE VRV ORIFICE.  AT 0312 HRS. PST ON 1/24/05, WITH THE TRAIN INSPECTION & SECUREMENT COMPLETED, THE HIGHWAYS WERE REOPENED.  FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL FRA-05010028 WAS GRANTED TO TRANSPORT GATX 75680 TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR PRODUCT UNLOADING & VRV REPLACEMENT.

column168: DURING A ROLL-BY TRAIN INSPECTION, BN 875065 WAS REPORTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM BOTTOM OUTLET AREA AND THE BNSF TRAIN CREW WAS NOTIFIED.  TRAIN WAS STOPPED AT WATER WORKS STATION WERE THE ST. JOSEPH F.D RESPONDED TO ASSIST AND TO STOP PRODUCT LEAK.  F. D. RESPONDERS PLACED PLASTIC SHEETING AND CONTAINMENT UNDER THE LEAK AREA.  THE LEFT SIDE T-COUPLING TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS LEAKING AT A BOLTED JOINT.  THE F.D RESPONDERS LOOSENED THE BOLTED CONNECTION AND APPLIED DUCT TAPE AROUND THE DETERIORATED JOINT GASKET.  ONCE THE BOLTED CONNECTION WAS RESECURED, THE LEAK STOPPED.  AFTERWARDS, THE TRAIN PRECEDED TO THE NEXT STATION (NODAWAY) AND SETOUT BN 875065 IN THE SIDING FOR FURTHER INSPECTION BY THE BNSF MECHANICAL TEAM.  DETAILED INSPECTION BY THE BNSF MECHANICAL RESPONDERS INDICATED THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE'S (TOBOV) OPERATING ROD WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED (LESS THAN TWO FULL TURNS TO CLOSE THIS VALVE).  NO FURTHER PRODUCT LEAKAGE WAS NOTED AT NODAWAY STATION.  AFTER TOBOV WAS CLOSED AND ALL OTHER INSPECTIONS COMPLETED, BN 875065 WAS DEEMED SECURED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION.  A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE SPILLAGE AREA NEAR WATER WORKS FINDING A SIX INCH TRAIL OF LIGHTLY STAINED BALLAST THAT THEY DETERMINED DID NOT REQUIRE EXVACATION.  THE RECOVERED SPILLAGE AND PLASTIC SHEETING FROM THE WATER WORKS SITE WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT THE BNSF KANSAS CITY, KS YARD FACILITY UNDER EXISTING USED OIL AND OILY WASTE PROFILES.
column169: BN 875065 WILL BE CYCLED TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR REMOVAL OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET T-COUPLING OUTLETS, AS THESE OUTLET FITTINGS HAVE BEEN PROBLEMMATIC RECENTLY.

column168: ON JANUARY 6TH, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM, DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE KNOX LEE FACILITY (LONGVIEW, TX) TO INVESTIGATE A REPORTED LEAKING VALVE ON A HYDROGEN TRAILER.  DRIVER BROUGHT A FULL TRAILER WITH HIM IN THE EVENT THAT THE LEAKING VALVE COULD NOT BE CORRECTED ON THE SPOT.  AFTER CONFIRMING THE LEAK, DRIVER OPTED TO SWAP THE TRAILERS.  DRIVER SPOTTED THE FULL TRAILER ON THE LEVEL GRADE ASH ROAD, LOWERED THE LANDING GEAR, AND BEGAN TO PULL OUT FROM UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER, WHEN A SINK HOLE BELOW DRIVER'S SIDE LANDING GEAR GAVE WAY, AND THE TRAILER BEGAN TO ROLL.  DRIVER OBSERVED THE TRAILER BEGINNING TO ROLL.  DRIVER OBSERVED THE TRAILER BEGINNING TO ROLL IN HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR, AND IMMEDIATELY ACCELERATED AWAY FROM THE TRAILER AND DROVE TO THE REAR OF THE PLANT.  THE TRAILER SUBSEQUENTLY ROLLED ON ITS TOP.  THE STAINLESS STEEL VENT STACKS ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER WERE PUSHED UP WHEN THEY IMPACTED THE GROUND.  AS A RESULT, SIX VALVES WERE IMMEDIATELY SHEARED OFF, AND THEIR CONTENTS BEGAN TO VENT.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE SIX TUBES VENTED WITHIN ABOUT 90 SECONDS.  NO FLAMES WERE OBSERVED AND NO SECONDARY DAMAGE INDICATED THE PRESENCE OF FLAMES.  DURING THIS TIME DRIVER CALLED 911, AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED.  DRIVER TOLD PLANT OPERATORS IN THE AREA TO ORDER AN IMMEDIATE EVACUATION OF THE PLANT UPWIND.  DRIVER THEN CONTACTED THE RBO PLANT MANAGER, AND INFORMED HIM OF THE INCIDENT.  RED BALL MANAGEMENT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1:45 PM.  RED BALL TECHNICAL SUPPORT SPECIALIST ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM.  THE TRAILER WAS ASSESSED AND IT WAS CONCLUDED THAT THE REMAINING FULL TUBES COULD BE SAFELY VENTED BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO RIGHT THE TRAILER.  A VENT HOSE WAS ASSEMBLED AND EACH TUBE WAS SLOWLY VENTED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 PM THE TUBES WERE FULLY VENTED, AND THE CRANE COMPANY BEGAN RECOVERY.  ONCE RIGHTED, THE CONDITION OF THE TRAILER WAS ASSESSED AND NO DAMAGE TO LIGHTS, BRAKES, OR SUSPENSION SYSTEM WAS OBSERVED.  IT WAS CONCLUDED THAT THE TRAILER COULD BE SAFELY MOVED.
column169: THE DRIVER HAS MADE MANY TRIPS TO THE PLANT WITHOUT INCIDENT AND HAD NO REASON TO BELIEVE THAT THE ROADWAY WOULD NOT BEAR THE WEIGHT OF THE TRAILER.  THE LANDING GEAR COULD HAVE BEEN SECURED BY TIMBERS OR SUPPORT PLATES IN ORDER TO PREVENT THEM FROM SINKING IN THE GROUND.

column168: ON JANUARY 25, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:01 HOURS, A RAILWAY CAR ACFX 200133, LOADED WITH PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1267 PG III, WAS REPORTED LEAKING DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION BY LOUISIANA STATE POLICE (LSP) AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) MOSSVILLE LOUISIANA YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) BY THE SECONDARY CLOSURE CAP.  THE TOP-OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOPOV) WAS FOUND OPEN, AND THE VAPOR PLUG WAS FOUND LOOSE.  THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED TO THE SITE CLOSING THE TOBOV, SECURING THE BOV CAP, AND TIGHTENING THE VAPOR PLUG.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.

At the consignee's facility the carrier's driver, using a manual pallet jack, unloaded shipper’s shrink-wrapped pallets onto the consignee’s dock.  When the consignee’s receiver picked up one pallet some liquid began leaking from the bottom of a pail on the pallet.  The pail was located at the bottom of its pallet.  The receiver broke down the pallet and found that there was a hole in a crease in the bottom.  The driver stated that the shipment had been in the nose of the trailer.  There was no liquid where the pallet had been and there was no trail of liquid following the path of the pallet as it had been unloaded.  The consignee accepted the entire shipment with a notation of the leak.  No clean up of the carrier's equipment was needed.

column168: BNSF TRAIN SWITCHING IN RAILYARD DERAILED FIVE TANK CARS LADENED WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DUE TO WIDE GAGE CAUSED BY DEFECTIVE RAIL FASTENERS.  ALL FIVE RAILCARS REMAINED UPRIGHT BUT TWO OF THESE WERE BURIED TO THE FIELD SIDE OF THE YARD TRACK IN BALLAST AND MUD.  TILX 190447 & GATX 2574 RELEASED PRODUCT INTO THE GROUND FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES (BOV) THAT WERE DAMAGED IN THIS DERAILMENT.  THE BOV SKID PLATES SUSTAINED DAMAGES BUT PROTECTED THE BOV'S FROM CATASTROPHIC DAMAGE.  TILX 190447 HAD THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) ASSEMBLY SHEARED OFF.  THE BOV OPERATING HANDLE WAS SEVERELY BENT AND PARTIALLY OPENED THE BOV.  BNSF AND GALLUP F.D. RESPONDERS STOPPED PRODUCT RELEASE BY CLOSING THE BOV AT 1555 HRS. MST.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN TILX 190447 WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR ON 2/22/05.  THE THREE BNSF CREW MEMBERS ON THE DERAILING TRAIN COMPLAINED OF PRODUCT INHALATION EXPOSURE.  THEY WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR EXAMS AND X-RAYS THAT RESULTED IN NEGATIVE FINDINGS.  AFTERWARDS THEY WERE RELEASED BACK TO WORK WITH NO RESTRICTIONS.  THE NM STATE POLICE CLOSED PORTIONS OF US ROUTE 66 THAT WERE WITHIN 1000 FEET OF THE DERAILMENT SITE FOR LESS THAN THREE HOURS.  A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR SURVEYED THE PRODUCT RELEASE SITE DETERMINING THAT MOST ESCAPING PRODUCT EVAPORATED.

column168: ASSOCIATED PETROLEUM CARRIERS (APC) WAS MAKING A GASOLINE DELIVERY AT THE JUNCTION CONVENIENCE STORE LOCATED AT 969 BLACKSTOCK ROAD, PAULINE, SC.  THIS WAS A GRAVITY DROP AND THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS WERE MANIFOLDED TOGETHER.  APPARENTLY, BACK PRESSURE FORMED IN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS FORCING THE TIGHT FIT COUPLING TO COME LOOSE FROM THE HOSE CONNECTION, RESULTING IN APPROXIMATELY 330 GALLONS OF GASOLINE BEING SPILLED.  THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENT PADS TO HELP CONTAIN THE SPILL. The trailer involved in the incident (Quality Carriers Trailer #8526) was involved in an earlier incident on the same day within the terminal (See 5800 Report #E-2005010174 Tracking#218).  The operator reported to terminal personnel that the trailer was repaired.  IMTT personnel had initiated loading methanol into the trailer after completing a series of pre-loading checks following the IMTT procedure and work instruction.  The trailer had current DOT testing information on the plate.  Upon transferring the methanol a leak developed at the ring clamp on the external valve on the pump-off line.  The transfer was terminated and the leak was contained using a bucket.  The 275 gallons of methanol was removed from the truck and stored on-site in tank MGD-2.  The product owner will test the product for quality and either re-sell or dispose. The emptied trailer departed the facility.
column169: Carrier’s must use available technology to determine the adequacy of their equipment to transport hazardous materials and just not annually but after each lading system is manipulated for example during repairs or cleaning some/most operators remove bolt up gasketed fittings to facilitate cleaning or repairs but the trailer is not tested after re-assemble.

column168: An approximate 230-gallon release of a solution containing 12% nickel from a stainless steel tote occurred on January 18, 2005 at approximately 10:56 pm.  The Streetsboro Fire Department arrived onsite and temporarily contained and secured the site.  A hazmat response team was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup actions.  The impacted area on the asphalt pavement was initially neutralized with lime.  The neutralized spill cleanup debris was containerized for transportation and disposal.  The area was cordoned off and power washed into a vacuum truck.  The impacted storm sewer section was power washed with a vacuum truck to remove contaminants.  The waste generated was containerized for transportation and disposal and the site was restored to its original conditions.    The cause of the release in under investigation at this time.

According to the information obtained while taking a sample at the consignee, Coleman Group One's location there was a blockage in the bleed off valve.  Approximately, one gallon of free product released. One employee had some of the free product splash in his eyes.  The employee flushed his eyes with water and required no further medial attention. Coleman Group One performed the cleanup and will dispose of all waste generated.  No other injuries or exposures were reported.  Clean up is complete.

The trailer had current DOT testing information on the plate.  Upon transferring the methanol the loading line began to leak at a gasketed flange.  The transfer was terminated and the leak was contained using a bucket. The loading hose and loading line was blown back to the trailer and the internal valve closed on the trailer.  The leak continued indicating that the internal valve was also not holding.  The methanol was removed from the truck by vacuum truck and stored in tank MGD-2. The product owner will test the product for quality and either re-sell or dispose. The emptied trailer departed the facility.
column169: Carrier’s must use available technology to determine the adequacy of their equipment to transport hazardous materials and just not annually but after each lading system is manipulated for example during repairs or cleaning some/most operators remove bolt up gasketed fittings to facilitate cleaning or repair but the trailer is not tested after re-assemble.

column168: A DAMAGED 55-GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED DURING THE UNLOADING OF A TRAILER THAT WAS BACKED UP TO THE MENLO DAYTON HUB TRUCK DOCK (DOOR 50).  THE DRUM (1 OF 3 TOTAL IN THE SHIPMENT) HAD TIPPED OVER SIDEWAYS WHEN THE DRUM SLID OUT FROM UNDER A SECUREMENT BAND THAT WAS HOLDING THE 3 DRUMS TO A PLASTIC PALLET UNDER THE DRUMS.  THE TIPPED DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AND APPROXIMATELY 7 GALLONS OF FLUID LEAKED ONTO THE BED OF THE TRAILER.  THE MENLO ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM (ERT) WAS CALLED TO THE TRAILER AT THE TRUCK DOCK UPON DISCOVERY OF THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE ERT REMOVED AND OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE FLUID FROM THE TRUCK BED USING A VARIETY OF ABSORBENT PADS.  THE DRUM IS CURRENTLY STAGED AWAITING FINAL DISPOSAL THROUGH A WASTE DISPOSAL CONTRACTOR.
column169: BANDING THE DRUMS TO A STANDARD WOODEN PALLET WOULD BE MORE EFFECTIVE THAN TO THE PLASTIC PALLET THAT WAS USED.  THE SMOOTH PLASTIC APPEARS TO HAVE ALLOWED THE DRUMS TO SHIFT UNDER THE SECUREMENT BANDS, RESULTING IN ONE DRUM BECOMING UNSECURED AND SUBSEQUENTLY TIPPING OVER.

A Weatherford employee was driving a chemical truck to an oilfield location when he drove off of the roadway onto the steep shoulder. This resulted in the vehicle rolling over 180 degrees and coming to rest upside down. The remainder of the crew in convoy immediately dug trenches and filled them with chemical absorbent pads to contain the material that was leaking. The Supervisor in charge contacted the District Manager. He contacted our Environmental Department at the Weatherford Corporate office in Houston, TX. They dispatched HAZMAT response teams from ort Worth, TX and Texarkana, TX. The local fire Department (Troup, TX) and the Texas Department of Public Safety were called to the scene. A representative from Texas TNRCC was also dispatched to the scene. The chemical totes were still attached to the truck by straps. The straps were cut, the truck lifted off of the totes and each tote was righted. An inventory of all material was taken and compared to the manifest to determine spilled quantities. The contaminated soil was removed by the HAZMAT team (Highway 59 Hazmat, Texarkana, TX) and taken for disposal. The dirt and fence were replaced. The wrecked vehicle was towed back to its home District. All remaining chemicals were transported via truck to the originating district. No citations were issued at the site.
column169: We will have the driver repeat Smith System defensive driving. In addition we will have him participate in a behavior based safety program (SafeStart)to prevent complacency and raise awareness.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon unloading at the Port of Houston in La Porte, Texas, a leak was discovered coming from the 20 foot container box.  The Houston Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Upon arrival, the Houston Fire Department applied absorbent pads to the minimal free product on the affected asphalt.  Dow Chemical Company was contacted to discuss response actions.  Garner Environmental Services of Deer Park, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection, it was determined that one (1) 55-gallon drum inside the container, had a small hole in the bottom of the drum, due to friction in transit.  Garner Environmental Services offloaded the container, and applied absorbent material to the free product.  Approximately 15 gallons of free product were released.  The majority of free product was contained inside the container, and approximately one gallon had released to the asphalt surface.  The damaged 55-gallon drum was overpacked, and left on site along with one (1) 55-gallon recovery drum which contained the spent absorbent material and PPE.  Dow Chemical Company will coordinate disposition/disposal of the two (2) recovery drums, per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and occurred due to friction in transit, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. will continue to enforce safety guidelines to ensure proper handling and loading of freight.

OUR DRIVER CAME BACK TO OUR WAREHOUE IN ALBUQUERQUE, NM WITH ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID THAT HE COULD NOT DELIVER TO HIS LAST CUSTOMER.  AFTER BACKING THE TRAILER INTO DOCK OUR RECEIVER OPENED THE DOOR AND SAW THE DRUM LAYING ON ITS SIDE AND LEAKING FLUID.  THE TRAILER HAD A CLOUD OF FUMES, ALSO AROUND THE DRUM. THE RECEIVER AND HE DRIVER PUT THE DRUM ON A WOOD PALLET, REMOVED BOTH FROM THE TRAILER AND PLACED THEM OUTSIDE IN OR PARKING AREA.  THE DRUM WAS SECURED ON THE PALLET IN A POSITION THAT STOPPED THE LEAK.  ALBUQUERQUE FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE CALLED TO SECURE, STABILIZE AND ISOLATE.  NEW MEXICO STATE POLICE ALSO CAME OUT AND OKAYED THE SECUREMENT.  THE OFFICER DID MAKE A REPORT.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING RINCHEM COMPANY,INC. FINISHED THE CLEANUP BY PUTTING THE HAZMAT INTO POLY SALVAGE OVER PACK DRUM, AND CLEANING THE HAZARDOUS DEBRIS WITH KITTY LITTER.

column168: IMTT personnel had initiated loading 50% sodium hydroxide solution into the trailer (Linden Trucking Trailer#T-55) after completing a series of pre-loading checks following the IMTT procedure and work instruction.  The trailer had current DOT testing information on the plate.  Upon transferring the sodium hydroxide solution the driver missed the stop gauge causing the trailer to overfill spilling the sodium hydroxide from the dome hatch.  The transfer was terminated and the leak was contained in the secondary containment surrounding the loading rack.  The outside of the trailer was decontaminated and the contaminated snow and water from snow melt within the secondary containment was removed and placed in an on-site storage tank.  Approximately 1,000 gallons of contaminated snow and water was recovered.
column169: IMTT determined that inattention and unfamiliarity of the driver with the trailer was the root cause.

column168: Two inch NPT plug removed from bottom flange and unloading fitting attached.  Unloading contents of rail car into production via bottom outlet of tank car.  Moving force supplied by 40 psi air pressure applied to top of tank car through air induction valve.  After unloading approximately 4000 lbs of material, the gasket on the outlet side of auxillary valve failed allowing contents to spray out from between the flange faces for approximately 5 minutes before auxillary valve was closed stopping the flow. column169: Improvements for this incident relate to off-loading contents rather than transportation issues.  Rather than off-loading with air pressure, a centrifugal pump will be used to pump the material from the tank cars.  An electric pump can pump turned off remotely thus stopping the pumping action.  When using air pressure, pressure remains on the car until this pressure can be released safely, this pressure is what provides the force needed to move the material.

column168: While loading the material, the driver created vaccum in the tank being loaded. Since this action did not improve the efficiency of the loading operation, the driver relieved the vacuum in the tank by manually opening the travel valve on the top of the tank. At the completion of the loading operation, the driver failed to secure the travel valve before departing from the shipper’s location. The shipper also neglected to inspect the vehicle prior to releasing the driver. While in transit, material sprayed from the open travel valve and was reported by a motorist to the LA State Police. The LA State Police responded and pulled over the truck. It was at this time that additional material was released from the valve and impacted the State Police vehicle. The local fire department and EMS were dispatched to the scene along with a member of the LA State Police Hazardous Materials Unit. Two individuals were transported via ambulance to a local hosptial where they were treated and released for potential exposure to the flammable liquid. The open valve was closed and the vehicles were transported to Clean Harbors’ Sulphur LA facility where they were washed and decontaminated.  Attached please find copies of police and fire reports.

column168: The release was a result of an overfill of the diesel fuel in an aboveground storage tank (AST) during rsfueling activities at the Garner’s General Store, located at 215 SW Elm Street, in Billings, Missouri, on January 17, 2005. Fuel spilled into the AST concrete containment; however, a missing plug for the containment allowed diesel fuel to migrate onto the gravel/asphalt parking area in the vicinity of the AST and into a grass-covered drainage ditch to the northwest AST. Store personnel notified the Billings Fire Department of the release. The Fire Department responded to the release and applied absorbent material to limit migration of the fuel. The incident was reported to the Missouri Department of Natural Resources (MDNR) and Issued incident #O5O11710Q8BWH. A backhoe was used to remove impacted soil and gravel to a depth of approximately 6-8 Inches from an approximately 15-foot by 5-foot area adjacent to the release point and a 5-foot by 6-foot area in the drainage ditch to the northwest of the release point. Absorbent materials were utilized to manually remove spilled diesel fuel from the asphalt portion of the parking area to the northwest of the AST containment. A vacuum truck was utiilzed to remove diesel fuel and water from the AST containment.  During excavation activities, soil was removed until no olfactory or visual indication of hydrocarbon impact remained. The impacted soil, gravel and absorbent material were profiled and transported to the Springfield Sanitary Landfill, in Springfield, Missouri. Approximately 150-gallons of diesel fuel and water were disposed of by Used Oil Services, in Springdele, Arkansas.
column169: The overfill alarm was repaired and missing containment plug was replaced by the manager/owner of the Garners General Store following the overfill,

column168: The driver was headed southbound on I-15 to Butte, Montana with full truckload of gasoline when the truck appeared the veered off to the right side of the road.  After driver realized truck was heading off the highway, he overcorrected causing the unit to overturned.  Body tank was separated from the truck and lost dome lid and released product.  Also, the pull trailer rolled which caused a small crack in the trailer and product was leaking slowly.  After the accident, emergency responders showed up on site, stopped the leak until other transport truck showed up to pump off the trailer and body tank.  Once both units were emptied, the equipment was towed from accident site to a storage yard in Helena, MT.  Environmental consultants and spill reponse team were informed to start immediate clean-up of the affected spill area.  All contaminated soils were excavated and placed on plastic sheeting until accepted at certified waste site.  The site has been completely remediated and contaminated soils have been disposed of at certified landfill.
column169: No recommendation.  We feel it was human error.

column169: THE HOSE THAT RUPTURED WAS RATED AT 120PSI. OPERATING ON A PUMP RATED AT 30 PSI..  THE HOSE SHOWED NO EXTERNAL DAMAGE OR WARE.  AFTER THE FAILURE THE INSIDE OF THE HOSE WAS EXAMINED AND A DAMAGED COIL WAS FOUND.  THAT COIL CAUSED THE FAILURE.  NO CHANGE IN TRAINING OR PROCEDURE COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT, BECAUSE THE DAMAGE TO THE HOSE WAS NOT VISIBLE.

WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS LAST DELIVERY LOCATION OF THE DAY, HE DISCOVERED A BROKEN PALLET AND A 55 GALLON DRUM OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION THAT HAD SHIFTED FORWARD HITTING A DRUM LOCATED DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF IT.  THE TOP RING ON THE DRUM THAT SHIFTED FORWARD PUNCTURED A HOLE ABOUT 2 1/2 INCHES LONG NEAR THE TOP OF THE ABOVE MENTIONED DRUM.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON WAS SPILLED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED AND THE DRIVER MOPPED THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO AN EMPTY DRUM.
column169: THE TRAILER WAS LOADED CORRECTLY IN ACCORDANCE WITH FMCSA PART 393.110.  THE DRIVER PERFORMED HIS PRE-TRIP AND EN ROUTE INSPECTIONS AT EACH DELIVERY LOCATION.  THIS EVIDENTALLY HAPPENED AFTER DEPARTING FROM HIS NEXT TO LAST DELIVERY BUT PRIOR TO ARRIVING AT HIS LAST.  WE WILL INSTRUCT OUR DRUM FILLERS TO CHECK THE PALLETS THROUGHLY BEFORE PLACING DRUMS ON THEM.

THE VENT LINE INLET AT THE SCRUBBER WAS UNPLUGGED AND CLEANED.  UNLOADING WAS RESTARTED WITH NO ADDITIONAL INCIDENTS.

column168: THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (LDEQ) NOW HAS AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE DIVISION AND IS CURRENTLY INSPECTING RAILCARS FOR FUGITIVE EMISSIONS, AS THE EMISSIONS MAY POSSIBLY IMPACT THE AIR QUALITY OF NON-ATTAINMENT AREAS.  THE LDEQ IS FOCUSING ON A CERTAIN COMMODITY GROUP AND ARE NOT INSPECTING FOR LEAKS WITH CONVENTIONAL MEANS.  THEY ARE USING PID (PHOTO IONIZATION DETECTION) AND FID (FLAME IONIZING DETECTION).  ON JANUARY 5, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 11:25 HOURS, RAILWAY CAR UTLX 48186, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINING ISOBUTYLENE, FLAMMABLE GAS, UN1055 WAS REPORTED LEAKING DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND THE LDEQ AT THE MARYLAND, LOUISIANA KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) RAIL YARD.  THE LDEQ DETECTED A LEAK USING A FIELD INSTRUMENT (IN VERY LOW PART PER MILLION (PPM)).  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WHO DISCOVERED TWO LOOSE LIQUID LINE PLUGS AND A LOOSE VAPOR LINE PLUG (HAND TIGHT).  THE TEAM TIGHTENED THE PLUGS, THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.  NOTE: PART III QUESTION 32, RESPONSE COST, INCLUDES CARRIER AND SHIPPER COSTS ONLY.  PART II, QUESTION 25 (CAUSE CODES).  THERE WERE NO DEFECTIVE VALVES OR DEVICE FAILURES, ONLY LOOSE CLOSURES, WHICH WERE SECURED SIMPLY BY TIGHTENING THE CLOSURE.  QUESTION 28 (IF VALVE OR DEVICE FAILED) NO TYPE, MANUFACTURER, OR MODEL NUMBER IS MARKED, SINCE THERE WERE ONLY LOOSE CLOSURES.
column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR, AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH RELEASE INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: Carrier discovered a strong ammonia odor from their transport vehicle at their terminal following overnight storage of cylinders they had picked up from us.   The carrier contacted our corporate office for assistance.  It was decided to contact an environmental clean-up/response contractor to come and initiate a repair.  One cylinder was discovered to be leaking from the valve stem.  The responders were unable to stop the leak by tightening the packing nut, so they installed a secondary capping device on the cylinder.  This stopped the leak.  There were no off-site complaints of ammonia odor, no evacuations were made, and no injuries reported.   Less than 5 pounds of product was estimated to have been released.

column168: The carrier driver called into his dispatcher to report that he was making delivery to the consignee.  The shipment of drums had been tendered to Jevic Transportation on pallets.  The drums were removed from the pallets and put on the floor to facilitate cargo capacity in the trailer.  The consignee would not accept the shipment unless it was on pallets, but they would allow the driver to put the drums onto pallets from their stock.      While rolling the drums onto the pallets, the driver came into contact with some residue on the side of a drum containing phosphoric acid solution.  The driver was wearing gloves at the time.  The material wet the gloves and the calf area of his pants legs.  He washed the affected areas of his skin and contacted the HazMat Department of his company.  He stated that he did not feel any ill effects at the time, and wished to continue on his route.    He called again from his next stop reporting that he feels some burning sensation to the affected areas of his legs.  The Jevic HazMat Department directed him to go to a nearby medical facility for evaluation and possible treatment.  The driver was found by the hospital to have moderate acid burns to legs and thighs.

column168: On January 6, 2005, Framatome ANP, INC., located out of Lyñchburg, Virginia, shipped a new empty non-specification container (made of sheet metal) that contained a slightly radioactive contaminated bag. The contaminated bag was to be used as cover for the equipment to be loaded once at Catawba Nuclear Station (CNS). This empty package was loaded onto a low-boy type flatbed trailer that was being transported by Duke Power to Catawba Nuclear Station for the purposes of loading it with a Reactor Coolant Pump Motor. Due to the slightly contaminated cover bag inside the new empty container, the shipping description used for the shipment was “Radioactive Material, excepted package-limited quantity of material, 7, UN2910, Limited Quantity.”  Around 1:45pm, enroute to CNS, the new empty container with the slightly radioactively contaminated bag bumped into the under part of an overpass bridge on 1-85 South at Exit 68 in China Grove, Rowan County, North Carolina. A 2 foot by 2 inch tear had been made into the empty container. Pictures of both the damaged container and minor scrapes on the bridge have been included.  Framatome ANP and CNS were notified. Framatome ANP came to China Grove and surveyed the top and outer sides and detected no contamination. The 2 foot by 2 in metal strip from the tear was also removed and determined to be clean. No contamination was on the top of the container where the tear was made. At no time were there any releases of radioactivity, radiation exposure or personnel injuries associated with this event. The tear was repaired.  The decision was made by the dispatcher and driver to notify NCDOT (Bridge Maintenance) so that damage to the bridge could be evaluated. NCDOT Bridge Maintenance and Duke Power Safety met at the site to measure the height of the bridge at the point of impact and to access the bridge for any damage. Other than minor scrapes along the metal beams of the bridge, there was no damage to the bridge.  The route that the driver was following was DOT approved for height and width of the load being transported. During the trip from Framatome to CNS, the truck was escorted in the front by another Duke Power vehicle. The escort vehicle had a pole attached to help with height determination. The escort vehicle did not detect a height problem when it went under the bridge. DOT approved the route for the load height of 15 foot 9 inches. The measured point of impact in the travel lane was 15 foot 11 inches. The information for the bridge provided from DOT statistics state that the bridge clearance was 16 foot 6 inches.  On 1/10/05, 8 am, Chuck Denny was made aware of the incident. On 1/10/05, 9:15 Miss  Jones, 1-800-424-8802, from the National Response Center was notified of the DOT incident it was stressed that no release was made. She issued the DOT Incident Number of 746648 for the DOT Incident.
column169: An escort vehicle was used for the tractor trailer involved in this incident. However, even though the escort vehicle used a pole that was 4 inches longer than the height of the escorted vehicle, the escort vehicle did not detect the height constraint and the package on the escorted vehicle hit the underside of the bridge when passing underneath it. It is believed that the pole used on the escort vehicle bent slightly and did not indicate the height concern. In addition, it is believed that the trailer may have tilted slightly to one side making the height a couple of inches higher. In the future, the vehicle will increase the pole length to ensure that it will better reflect the height of the escorted vehicle. The escort vehicle is also evaluating a pole that will electronically signal the escort vehicle driver if the pole hits anything.  NCDOT records indicate that the bridge had vertical clearance 16 foot 6 inches. This is 7 inches over the vertical height of point of impact, 15 foot 11 inches. We are now aware of how much the bridges recorded clearances can be off.

After connecting to the trailer our Driver performed the ground level portion of his  pre-trip inspection but failed to inspect the dome lids on top of the trailer.There were two lids and the forward lid was not secured. After leaving the shipper's property the unit travelled about 3/4 mile to a stop light at the intersection  of Old Dixie Hwy and Johnson St. When the Driver applied his brakes to stop at the  light about 20 gallons of product escaped via the front dome lid. Spilled product was  contained to the general area using sand as absorbent. Contaminated sand and product  disposed of by Holter Services.
column169: Company policies and procedures and Federal requirements pertaining to Motor Vehicle  Inspections and Cargo Tank Inspections were reveiwed with this Driver.   Communication is made in Monthly Safety Meetings to review incidents with all Drivers.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: The cargo tank driver verified the storage tank level against the level indicator and with plant personnel and that the storage tank could hold the total contents of his cargo tank.  During the unloading process, the driver noticed liquid coming out the tank vent.  He immediately shut off his unloading pump.  Approximately 1 quart spilled down the side of the tank.  Plant personnel washed off the tank.
column169: The plant checked the calibration of their storage tank level device prior to the next delivery.  Also the the driver was instructed to monitor the storage tank's level indication throughout the unloading process to help determine if the level is going up as anticipated. This will help confirm the level device's calibration is correct.

While unloading an ocean container at the Jacksonville Distribution Center a forklift driver was using the forks to pry up the toe board dunnage.  The boards broke suddenly and the forks punctured the HDPE drum, causing the spill.  The hole was about 1x5 inches in the drum.    The drum weas turned over to stop the immediate discharge and our internal spill containment process was initiated,
column169: The unloading staff was retrained in removing the toe boards properly.    The spill was remediated using an EPA registered contractor and the waste was packed into overpacks for incineration at an EPA approved incinerator.

Motor carrier driver was using pressure to transfer shipment from cargo tank trailer to storage tank. Consignee failed to remove/reduce pressure in plant system to allow shipment to be transferred. Normal plant system pressure was reported to be 58 psi. Stored material was transferred from the storage tank into the cargo tank trailer and the trailer was overfilled causing release. Driver switched from pressure unloading to pump unloading and the shipment was successfully transferred. Material lost from over fill and swithching hoses for pump unloading.
column169: Carrier will alert drivers to this consignee pressure problem. Drivers to ensure that consignee unloader removes pressure from system before transfer is attempted.

column168: File #E-2005010047 / Shipper:  TIC-The Industrial Company / AWB # WDN 7632179435 NEW    On 01-04-05 at 0313 an outside leaking labpack was reported in C building (express area lateral 14) of our main sort facility located at ABX Air, Inc., 145 Hunter Drive, Wilmington, Ohio 45177.  Part time spill technician Kenneth Oppy donned proper personal protective equipment and responded.  Upon arrival he found a plastic lab pack with visible signs of leakage on the outer package.  He removed the lab pack from the area and began his investigation.  Upon investigation he found this lab pack to contain 8 plastic specimen cups that contained and unknown liquid.  The closures on these specimen cups were not secured by positive means.  The closure on one cup was loose allowing it to leak approximately 1 ounce of its contents.  This leaked outside of the lab pack.  This packaged arrived in Wilmington on Flyt #0413, N775AX.    This lab pack was marked "Overwrap for Diagnostic Shipments".    As a precaution, the area involved was thoroughly cleaned with bleach before normal operations were resumed.    The part time spill technician sealed and bagged the lab pack in tow plastic bags with absorbent material and placed it into a salvage drum.  This shipment was forwarded to its destination.    Clear of scene:  0315.    There are pictures on file in the Haz Mat office located in Wilmnigton, Ohio.
column169: Specimen cups should have positive means of closure.

column168: Arcie Sapp, Transport driver was delivering fuel to Marshall BP, he went into the office to get hot water to pour on lock ,then went back to tank.  Five minutes into fuel unloading there was an explosion.  Plant employees evacuated to highway and called 911.  Fire department arrived in approximately 3 minutes, Arcie had wondered out of corn field in 2-5 minutes.  Fire department personnel put him in pickup to take him to ambulance.  Arcie went to Marshall hospital and was then airlifted to University of Missouri hospital in Columbia.  Fire department used 30-40 million gallons of water on fire, hauled 7-8 loads of contaminated fuel to Kansas City for recycling and used collection ponds on neoghboring property to catch water.  Transport vehicle had 8323 gallons NL.  Tanks at location had 13815 gals of NL, 17627 gals of SNL, 8375 gals clear diesel, 14699 gals red diesel lost in fire/explosion.
column169: Looking at new vents, fire retardant clothing, new company procedures.

column168: Timothy Williams was filling a propane tank from his truck. While pumping he thought the pump was going to stop. He checked the strainer on the meter and found gasket was leaking. He loosened bolts to repair, the gas that was in the strainer sprayed on him. He sustained first degree burns. He was treated in the Emergency Room and released.     There was a quick release of approximately one gallon.

ON 1/28/2005 DRIVER BOB CUMMINGHAM ARRIVED @ 145 DONOHUE RD GREENSBURG PA HE OPENED HIS TRAILER DOOR & WITNESSED A CLOUD OF WHITE SMOKE EMIT FROM THE TRAILER, HE CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR.  MOVED IT TO A SECURE AREA & CALLED THE TRANSPORTATION DEPT @ ORGILL INWOOD WV.  WE THEN CALLED PROFESSIONAL EMERGENCY RESOURCE SERVICES, WHO THEN CONTACTED THE NEUTELIN GROUP.  WHO REPORTED TO THE SIGHT FOR CLEAN UP.  THE DRIVER HAD ISOLATED THE TRAILER & SET OUT HIS SPILL KIT.  A GALLON CONTAINER OF MURATIC ACID HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A 1/2" PIECE OF METAL CONDIUT.

JAVIER RODRIGUEZ, DRIVER FOR MTS STIMULATION SERVICES, INC. WAS DIRECTED INTO SCALE HOUSE FOR A VEHICLE INSPECTION.  AFTER THE SAFETY INSPECTION THE INSPECTOR NOTICED A WET SPOT UNDER THE TANKER.  THE INSPECTOR ALERTED MR. RODRIGUEZ OF A DRIP.  MR. RODRIGUEZ PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK AND PROCEEDED TO INSPECT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM A VITRIOLIC COUPLER GASKET ON THE TANKER MANIFOLD.  THE SCALE HOUSE WAS THEN CLOSED.  MR. RODRIGUEZ WIPED UP THE SMALL WET SPOT (APPROX. 1-2 OZ) WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD.  MR. RODRIGUEZ WAS INSTRUCTED TO SECURE A BUCKET UNDER THE SOURCE OF THE DRIP AND THEN MOVE THE VEHICLE TO A MORE REMOTE, SECURE SITE ON THE DIRT ABOUT 100 FT FROM THE FACILITY.  AT 7:15 A.M. THE KERN COUNTY FIRE DEPT HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED ON SCENE, WITH THE KERN COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH REPRESENTATIVE ARRIVING SHORTLY THEREAFTER.  ENVIRONMENTAL INSPECTOR CHECKED AND FOUND NO CONTAMINATION AT INITIAL SITE OF LEAK.  NO CONTAMINATION WAS FOUND UNDER THE TANKER UNIT.  AT THIS POINT THE GASKET HAD STOPPED LEAKING.  SHORTLY AFTER THIS TWO REPRESENTATIVES FROM MTS ARRIVED (TOMMY REED, PRESIDENT AND JOHN JOHNSTON, OPERATIONS MANAGER).  AFTER DISCUSSING THE SITUATION WITH ROGER PIERCE, CHP SERGEANT AND WESLEY NICKS, KERN COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH IT WAS DECIDED THAT MTS COULD SAFELY REPLACE THE GASKET ON SITE.  MR. RODRIGUEZ REPLACED THE GASKET AND WAS THEN ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON.
column169: UPON CLOSE EXAMINATON OF GASKET MATERIAL, IT SHOWED SIGNS OF DETERIORATION.  RESEARCHED AND FOUND A STRONGER GASKET MATERIAL SUITABLE FOR THE PRODUCTS WE HAUL.  WE WILL IMPLEMENT A MANDATORY POLICY OF CHANGING ALL MANIFOLD GASKETS AT THE TIME OF THEIR ANNUAL INSPECTION.

column168: AT 0630HRS ON 1-3-05, FRANK LERCH MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE BLOOMINGTON YARDMASTER AND ADVISED TANK CAR GATX 17855 WAS LEAKING.  THE YARDMASTER INDICATED THAT CAR WOULD LEAK FROM THE TOP ONLY WHEN IT WAS MOVED, AND WOULD STOP LEAKING WHEN THE CAR WAS STATIONARY.  THE CAR HAD BEEN SET-OUT IN TRACK SOUTH 12 FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  MR LERCH RESPONDED, AND ADVISED THE RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC.  UPON INSPECTION, LERCH NOTED THE FOUR NUTS SECURING THE EDUCTION LINE FLANGE WERE LOOSE AND THE EDUCTION LINE FLANGE GASKET WAS MISSING.  ADDITIONALLY, THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS WORN, AND MISPOSITIONED, HOWEVER THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE FROM THE MANWAY OPENING.  MGR. LERCH REPLACED BOTH THE MANWAY AND FLANGE GASKETS WITH GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL, AND TIGHTENED THE FOUR NUTS ON THE EDUCTION LINE FLANGE.  AFTER CORRECTING THE EXCEPTIONS, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP REQUIRED AS PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.  AT 1230 MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER, AND ADVISED KATHY CROSS, HEALTH & SAFETY MANAGER FOR FLINT HILL RESOURCES OF THE EXCEPTIONS.  SHE ADVISED THAT AFTER THE CAR IS OFF LOADED, IT WOULD SHOPPED FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.
column169: REVIEW PER AND POST INSPECTION PROCESS WITH LOADING RACK PERSONNEL, PRESSURE CHECK CAR PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: UPRR S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A TANK CAR LEAKING PRODUCT IN SALINA, KS.  TANK CAR GATX 76222 WAS DISCOVERED BY PAM GINGERICH, FRA HAZ-MAT INSPECTOR TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  LARRY MITCHELL WITH UNITED BIO ENERGY (SHIPPER) WAS NOTIFIED AND HE ADVISED PLANT PERSONNEL WOULD RESPOND TO CHECK THE CAR AND ATTEMPT TO SECURE THE VALVE.  LARRY MITCHELL WITH UNITED BIO ENERGY (SHIPPER) WAS NOTIFIED AND HE ADVISED PLANT PERSONNEL WOULD RESPOND TO CHECK THE CAR AND ATTEMPT TO SECURE THE VALVE.  DARRIN FROM THE RUSSELL UNITED BIO ENERGY PLANT MET MS. GINGERICH AT THE SALINA YARD AND INSPECTING THE CAR.  HE DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE AND UNABLE TO BE REPAIRED OR SECURED IN THE FIELD.  HE WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK BY REMOVING AND REINSTALLING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP TO THE VALVE OUTLET.  ON BEHALF OF THE SHIPPER, A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL WAS OBTAINED FROM THE FRA (FRA-05010020) TO ALLOW THE CAR TO MOVE BACK TO THE PLANT FOR UNLOADING AND THEN TO A REPAIR FACILITY.  NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED FROM THIS INCIDENT AT THE RATE OF RELEASE WAS EXTREMELY SMALL AND THE PRODUCT WAS EVAPORATING FAIRLY WELL.

column168: AT 09:21 PM ON 1-19-04, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED THAT PAUL DAY, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, ADVISED A CARMAN HAD REPORTED A FOUL ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR TILX 260884.  THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED ON THE EAST END OF BOWL TRACK 1 ON THE ENGLEWOOD YARD; HOUSTON, TX.  PAUL ADVISED THE CARMAN NOTED THE ODOR, BUT DID NOT OBSERVE ANY PHYSICAL LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT.  MGR LERCH RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, AND WHILE EN ROUTE, HE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TEXMARK, AND ADVISED LINDA SALINAS, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER OF A POSSIBLE RELEASE FROM THE CAR.  UPON INSPECTION OF CAR, LERCH DETECTED A SLIGHT ODOR COMING FROM THE CAR, AND NOTED FOUR OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS IN POSITION, NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  AFTER TIGHTENING THE SWING BOLTS APPROXIMATELY %. TO ONE THEN EACH, THE CAR WAS SECURED FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE, AND ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.  LINDA SALINAS, WAS ADVISED OF THE NOTED EXCEPTIONS, AND INDICATED THAT SHE WOULD FOLLOW-UP AND TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: FRANK LERCH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED AN EMPLOYEE AT THE SETTEGAST RAILYARD IN HOUSTON, TEXAS WAS SPLASHED WITH LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED FROM TANKCAR ACFX 76474 DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE YARD.  MR. LERCH STATED THE EMPLOYEE WAS UNINJURED AND WAS GOING TO HIS RESIDENCE TO CLEAN UP.  MR. LERCH ALSO STATED THE RAILCAR WOULD BE SET ASIDE AND THERE DIDN'T APPEAR TO BE ANY DAMAGE TO THE RAILCAR.  AT 9:05 AM, GEOFFREY REEDER, ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, REPORTED ONE GALLON OF THE FUEL SPILLED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE TANKCAR.  MR. REEDER ADVISED HE WAS ON SITE FOR REMEDIATION.  MR. REEDER STATED THE TANKCAR LEAKED DUE TO A MISSING PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE TANKCAR AND THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO THE GROUND.  JOHNNY CATHEY, HALLIBURTON ENERGY SERVICES, WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE SITUATION.  HALLIBURTON ARRANGED FOR RESCAR TO REPLACE THE MISSING PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  OIL MOP CLEANED THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR.  ON 1-25-05 MANAGER LERCH OVERSAW RESCAR PERSONNEL SECURE A NEW PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND OBSERVED THE CAR TO BE PRESSURE CHECKED.  CAR WAS FOUND TO BE SECURE, AND WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.
