column168: RICHARD WULFF, MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT SUPERINTENDENT, REPORTED INTERMODAL RAILCAR FEC 2785 WAS LEAKING IN THE ALTON AND SOUTHERN RAILYARD WHILE LOCATED ON TRACK 130.  MR. WULFF ADVISED THERE WAS NO EVACUATIONS OR INJURIES.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 06:24 PM, WULFF STATED IN EFFORTS TO INSPECT THE LOAD HE BROKE THE SEAL ON RAILCAR FEC 2785 AND LOCATED ONE FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUM COMPROMISED.  MILLER INSPECTED THE LOAD AND ADVISED THE SHIPPER OF RAILCAR FEC 2785 THAT THEY WILL NEED TO HAVE PERSONNEL RESPOND TO CLEAN THE INVOLVED CONTAINER AND HAVE THE FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUM REPAIRED BEFORE IT COULD CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.  THE RAILCAR AND CONTAINER WERE ISOLATED IN THE YARD.

column168: THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, ADVISED VAPOR WAS LEAKING FROM TANKCAR, DOWX 82033.  ROBINSON RELATED THAT PERSONNEL FROM THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAD BEEN INSPECTING TANK CARS AT THE UPRR LIVONIA YARD.  L-DEQ USING MONITORING EQUIPMENT DETERMINED THAT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON THIS TANK CAR REGISTERED 10,400 PPM MEASURING FOR VOLATILE ORGANIC COMPOUNDS.  FURTHER EXAMINATION INDICATED 4000 PPM AT THE THROAT OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  VISUAL EXAMINATION OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE INDICATED WETNESS AND A SLIGHT ODOR.  THE VALVES AND FITTINGS INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING DISPLAYED A LARGE AMOUNT OF RUST, CORROSION AND FLAKING PAINT.  MR. ROBINSON REQUESTED THE STATE OF LOUISIANA REGULATORY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.  AT 07:29 PM, THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, STATED DOW CHEMICAL HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS ON SCENE.  ON 01/12/05 AT 12:50 AM, ROBINSON ADVISED THAT THE RESPONSE CREW FROM DOW CHEMICAL MADE AN UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPT TO CHANGE THE "O" RINGS ON THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  MR ROBINSON ADVISED DOW'S RESPONSE CREW WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AND REQUESTED THE TANKCAR BE RETURNED TO DOW'S PLANT IN PLAQUEMINE, LA TO BE DEPRESSURIZED.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH UNION PACIFIC'S OPERATING DEPARTMENT AT LIVONIA TO PLACE THE TANKCAR BACK INTO THE DOW FACILITY THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  MR ROBINSON STATED MS. KAREN PRICE, LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, WAS ON SCENE AND APPROVED THE PLAN TO TRANSPORT THE TANKCAR TO THE DOW FACILITY.
column169: REPLACE AND OR REPAIR PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  CHECK FOR PRODUCT COMPATIBILITY.

column168: RYAN, CORRIDOR MANAGER, REPORTED AS TRAIN MMFSC1 12 WAS DEPARTING THE MILFORD, UT, RAILYARD.  TANKCAR UELX 78044 RUPTURED AND RELEASED 30,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  TAMMY, MILFORD FIRE DEPARTMENT, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED THEY WERE ON SCENE AT THIS TIME.  LEON HENDRICKSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 09:50 PM, TAMMY, MILFORD FIRE DEPARTMENT, REQUESTED TANKCAR INFORMATION FAXED TO THEIR OFFICE.  AT 10:15 PM, TAMMY, MILFORD FIRE DEPARTMENT, ADVISED THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO A ONE HUNDRED BY ONE HUNDRED YARD AREA.  ON 01/12/05 AT 12:14 AM, LES, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED THE TANKCAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED.  MR. HENDRICKSON ADVISED THAT ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS EN ROUTE AS WELL AS PACIFIC WEST, A UPRR CONTRACTOR WHO WOULD BE HANDLING REMEDIATION OF THE INCIDENT.  PACIFIC WEST USED VAC TRUCKS TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column168: TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, REPORTED A TWO TANKCAR DERAILMENT IN SEABROOK, TX, NEAR THE CROSSING OF PORT ROAD AND STATE ROUTE 146.  MR O'BRIEN STATED THE TWO RAILCARS WERE ON THEIR SIDES, LEAKING, AND THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS ON FIRE.  ADDITIONALLY, APPROXIMATELY 1200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM A DERAILED LOCOMOTIVE (UP190).  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE, AND THE CARS WERE UPRIGHTED TO STOP THE LEAKS.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKS FROM THE PEROXIDE CARS WERE THE "STONE" VENTS ON TOP OF THE CAR.  THE DIESEL FUEL WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH AND LOCOMOTIVE FUEL TANK USING A VACUUM TRUCK.  REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES WERE COMPLETED 1/17/05.

column168: PHOENIX YARD MASTER, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD REPORTED TANKCAR NATX 29888 WAS LEAKING IN TRACK 7 AT PHOENIX, AZ.  YARDMASTER STATED THE PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE TANKCAR AND HAD NOT POOLED YET.  BRIAN BEAZER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, ADVISED A CONTRACTOR WAS EN ROUTE TO REMEDIATE THE LEAK.  BEAZER REPORTED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ADAPTER FLANGE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ARRANGED FOR THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT TO HIGHWAY TRUCKS.  TANKCAR WAS OFF LOADED AND MADE READY FOR TRANSPORTATION TO TANKCAR SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  SHIPPER RECEIVED AN FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL AND SCHEDULED CAR FOR MOVEMENT FROM PHOENIX, AZ.

column58: Bolts or Nuts; Manway or Dome Cover
column168: CHAD CRABTREE, YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 64347, ON TRAIN ID QLIHL 07, WAS DERAILED ON ITS SIDE IN THE LIVONIA RAILYARD AT MILE POST 110.7 DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  WITH THE CAR ON ITS SIDE, A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPED FROM BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE COVER PLATE.  TOM ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, ARRIVED ON SCENE AND TIGHTENED THE BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  IN ADDITION, A SMALL BUCKET HAD BEEN PLACED BENEATH THE DRIP AS CONTAINMENT.  KATHERINE, DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED THAT TROOPER JASON POE, LOUISIANA STATE PATROL, WAS RESPONDING.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT BY RMCC.  ON 01/08/05, 03:15 AM, ROBINSON STATED ALL RAILCARS WERE RERAILED AND SITE REMEDIATION WAS COMPLETED.  HULCHER SERVICES USED SORBENT MATERIAL TO SOAK UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.
column169: LOCAL DERAILMENT PREVENTION COMMITTEE WILL REVIEW FOR DEVELOPMENT OF CORRECTIVE ACTIONS IF ANY.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: PHIL CAVALLERO, MANAGER INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED IM TANK UTCU 414034, LOCATED IN THE EAST LOS ANGELES YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, CA, WAS LEAKING.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 11:56PM, COOPER CONFIRMED THE IM TANK WAS RELEASING SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE FROM THE REAR DISCHARGE VALVE.  MR. COOPER STATED THE RELEASE WAS BY PASSING THE MAIN FOOT VALVE, THE SECONDARY BUTTERFLY VALVE, AND THE NOZZLE SCREW CAP CLOSURE.  INSPECTION OF THE NZOZLE AFTER THE CLOSURE CAP WAS REMOVED, NOTED RAGS HAD BEEN STUFFED INTO THE NOZZLE AT SOME TIME, IN AN ATTEMPT TO STP THE LEAK.  MR. COOPER REQUESTED RMCC NOTIFY CHEMTREC TO COORDINATE A CONFERENCE CALL WITH THE SHIPPER OF THE IM TANK.  ON 01/06/2005 AT 12:10 AM, COOPER ADVISED RMCC AND HALDIS FEARN, AMERICAN PRESIDENT REPRESENTATIVE, VIA CONFERENCE CALL, THAT HE HAD PLACED A GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL OVER THE EXISTING TEFLON CAP GASKET, AND SECURED IT IN PLACE TO TEMPORARILY REPAIR THE THREADED CAP CLOSURE ON THE NOZZLE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  MS. FEARN ADVISED SHE WOULD CONTACT STOLT TANK CONTAINERS AND APL LAND TRANSPORT TO COORDINATE A TRANSLOAD TO A NEW IM TANK IN THE MORNING.  MR. COOPER ADVISED HE WOULD PLACE THE IM TANK INTO BAD ORDER STATUS.  ON 1/11/05, VENTURA TRANSFER, UNDER INSTRUCTIONS FROM STOLT, HAD THE IM TANK 'FLIPPED' ONTO A PRIVATE CHASSIS, AND TRANSPORTED THE UNIT TO THEIR LONG BEACH FACILITY FOR REPAIRS.  THE IM TANK RETURNED TO THE EAST LOS ANGELES INTERMODAL FACILITY ON 1/20/05, WHERE IT WAS ONCE AGAIN INSPECTED BY MANAGER COOPER.  CABLE SEAL VTC 084541 WAS REMOVED FROM THE NOZZLE CLOSURE CAP, AND THE CAP LOOSENED.  BEFORE THE CAP WAS FULLY REMOVED, PRODUCT BEGAN DRIPPING FROM THE CLOSURE.  VENTURA WAS CONFERENCED ON A CALL WITH MANAGER COOPER, AND HALDIS FERN, FROM APL.  VENTURA STATED THEY REPAIRED THE SECONDARY BUTTERFLY VALVE, AS IT WAS THE ONLY VALVE THAT FAILED THE ORIGINAL VACUUM TEST.  THE TEFLON SEAT OF THE VALVE WAS REPLACE, AND BOTH VALVES WERE AGAIN TESTED AND FOUND TO HOLD.  VENTURA INDICATED THE PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE NOZZLE MAY BE FROM PRODUCT RESIDUE LOCATED BETWEEN THE INTERNAL FOOT VALVE AND THE BUTTERFLY VALVE, BUT COULD NOT EXPLAIN HOW PRODUCT GOT PAST BOTH VALVES TO THE DISCHARGE NOZZLE CLOSURE CAP.  APL RECORDS SHOWED THE ORIGINAL SHIPPERS CABLE SEAL ON THE SECONDARY BUTTERFLY VALVE AS SYMS 694287, WHICH WAS STILL INTACT ON THE LOCKING MECHANISM, ALONG WITH RIBBON SEAL COSTACO DL 950513, AND WIRE SEAL FTD A 257584.  APL ADVISED STOLT THE IM TANK WOULD REQUIRE A TRANSFER AS THE PRODUCT WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  ON 2/3/05, THE IM TANK WAS AGAIN MOVED TO THE VENTURA TRANSFER FACILITY, WHERE THE PRODUCT IS TO BE TRANSFERRED TO IM TANK SNIU 124123.  THE ORIGINAL IM TANK HAS YET TO BE ASSIGNED TO A REPAIR FACILITY.
column169: PROPER INSPECTION OF THE VALVES DURING THE LOADING PROCESS.

column168: (A)FILE-05-2 DOT SHIPPER-AMERICAN CHEMICAL AWB#-ELA 3872990822 DEN  (B)  FILE-05-4 DOT SHIPPER-AMERICAN CHEMICAL AWB#-ELA 3872990725 DEN  ON 01/05/2005, AT 0300 EST, THE HOTLINE RECEIVED A CALL REGARDING TWO UNDAMAGED HAZ SHIPMENT BOXES.  THESE-WERE DISCOVERED TO BE WET IN THE HAZMAT AREA.  AN EMPLOYEE REPORTED THEM TO THE HAZMAT INSPECTOR.  THE HAZMAT INSPECTOR REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE AREA MANAGER AT THE FRESNO STATION.  THE MANAGEMENT AT THE FRESNO STATION CALLED THE HAZMAT HOTLINE TO REPORT THE SPILL.  THE HOTLIEN CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TO INVESTIGATE THE LEAKING SHIPMENT.  UPON INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO CONTAIN 2 X 250 ML PLASTIC BOTTLES THAT WERE CONTAINED INSIDE A PLASTIC ZIPLIC BAG, WITH PACKING PEANUTS.  THE BOTTLES DID NOT HAVE POSITIVE MEANS OF CLOSURE, ALLOWING THEM TO LEAK.  THIS PACKAGE ARRIVED IN FRESNO ON S SS TRUCK FLIGHT #4499.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, AND DID HAVE A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO INDICATE THAT IT WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE RESPONSE TEAM PLACED THE SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1235.

THE SUPERVISOR AT THE STATION ADVISED THAT THE RECEIVER HAD REFUSED THE SHIPMENT SAYING THE INNER CONTENTS WERE COMPROMISED.  THE BOX HAS NO OUTWARD APPEARANCE OF A LEAK.  THE PACKAGE ARRIVED AT THE BURLINGTON STATION ON FLIGHT #154, N949AX.  THE HAZMAT HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TO INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT.  UPON INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 4 X 1 LITER GLASS BOTTLES OF "ACETONITRILE."  ONE OF THE GLASS BOTTLES WAS BROKEN ALLOWING IT TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  THE PACKAGE HAD ENOUGH ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN THE LEAK TO THE INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND DID HAVE A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE RESPONSE TEAM PLACED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1810

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: WHEN PRO NUMBER 175-556522 WAS DISCOVERED THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY (JUSTIN VOWELS) WAS NOTIFIED.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO CALL HIS SAFETY SUPERVISOR FOR INSTRUCTIONS OF WHAT TO DO.  WE CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND PLACED ALL THE LEAKING AND SATURATED CONTAINERS INSIDE A HAZMAT RECOVERY DRUM.  WE PLACED 4 1GAL PAILS INSIDE A 5 GAL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE SPILL APPEARS TO HAVE ACURED WHILE LOADING AND THEN DRYED IN TRANSIT.  THE FREIGHT WAS DAMAGED ON THE CORNER OF THE PALLET AND 1 CASE WAS PUNCTURED WITH 2 1 GAL PAILS INSIDE THAT WERE PUNCTURED AND LEAKING.
column169: THE LOADER NEED TO BE MORE AWARE OF HIS SURROUNDINGS.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE GIVING OFF VERY STRONG PETROLEUM-BASED ODORS.  THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT BY OUR HAZMAT TEAM & OPENED.  WE FOUND AN UNDETERMINED NUMBER OF CARBURATORS, LEAKING WHAT WE BELIEVE TO BE GASOLINE.  THERE WERE NO SHIPPING PAPERS, MARKINGS, LABELING, OR EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA JOE BALLAS.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: MICHAEL BRAZILLE, YARDMASTER, REPORTED LOADED TANKCAR SHPX 207165 WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY COVER ONTO THE SIDES OF THE TANKCAR IN THE SETTEGAST RAILYARD HOUSTON, TX.  TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  UPON INSPECTING THE TANK CAR, MR. O'BRIEN FOUND THE MANWAY COVER PLATE MISALIGNED.  THE GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND THE COVER PLATE REPOSITIONED AND THE CAR SECURED.

column58: Bolts or Nuts; Manway or Dome Cover
column168: MR KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC ABOUT AN ODOR COMING FROM TRACK #56.  MR SIMPSON RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT TANK CAR UTLX 57871 HAD SEVEN LOOSE MANWAY BOLTS.  HE TIGHTENED ALL SEVEN MANWAY BOLTS AND REINSPECTED THE TANK CAR.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.
